      "narrative": {
        "News": "GCC Bunkers - Galveston: the 50,000 bpd CDU was restarted during the morning of July 2. The unit was observed to be offline as of the afternoon of June 25. The exact timing of the shutdown is unknown due to a temporary camera outage. Shell - Norco: significant elevated flaring began during the after- noon of July 1 (EST). Similar flaring has previously been associat- ed with operational issues and maintenance. Activity at all moni- tored units remained unchanged.",
        "Ongoing Events": "TotalEnergies - Port Arthur: the 80,000 bpd CDU and 52,000 bpd VDU were restarted during the morning of June 30. In- creased activity began at the 80,000 bpd FCC during the morning of June 27, but remained below operational levels. Also, increased activity halted at the 165,000 bpd CDU and 55,000 bpd VDU dur- ing the morning of June 28 after beginning June 25. Increased ac- tivity continued at the 60,000 bpd coker, 10,000 bpd coker naph- tha hydrotreater, 66,000 bpd ULSD hydrotreater, 39,600 bpd cat- alytic reformer and 45,500 bpd reformer feed hydrotreater since the afternoon of June 25. All monitored units were shut during the late evening of June 19. Marathon - El Paso: the 66,000 bpd CDU, 17,350 bpd VDU and 18,000 bpd catalytic reformer were restarted during the morning of June 30. Increased activity began at the crude section during the morning of June 28 after it shut during the evening of June 24. In- creased activity began at the catalytic reformer during the morning of June 26 after it shut during the morning of June 25. Citgo - Corpus Christi: the 44,000 bpd coker was restarted dur- ing the morning of June 20. Increased activity began at the unit during the evening of June 17. The unit was shut on June 14. The 174,000 bpd CDU and 85,300 bpd VDU were shut during the late morning of June 18 and remained offline. The units were ini- tially shut on June 10. Exxon - Baytown: significant elevated flaring began during the morning of June 18. Similar flaring has previously been associated with operational issues and maintenance. Activity at all monitored units remained unchanged. Also at the refinery, decreased activity continued at the 314,000 bpd and 115,000 bpd CDUs since May 1 and May 26, respectively. The company reported an operational upset resulting in flaring and noise on June 18, according to a community notification. PBF - Chalmette: the 19,000 bpd catalytic reformer was shut dur- ing the afternoon of May 8. A fire was reported at the facility. Phillips 66 - Sweeny: the 30,000 bpd FCC was shut during the af- ternoon of March 28. Decreased furnace stack activity began at that time.",
        "Planned Maintenance": ""
      }
